f=Cybersecurity/warden/custom/security-policy-framework/SKILL.md · in=warden's ISMS: Information Security Management System org's security control catalog mapped chosen standard (NIST CSF ISO 27001 SOC CIS), policy set implements it, mapping controls agents/operators who them. **control content** comes marketplace GRC pack chosen standard; **this skill wraps it** mapping, ownership, gap-tracking pack doesn't provide. · p=Security without framework pile hoc rules nobody audit. standard-mapped ISMS makes "are secure" checkable question: control owner, status, evidence gaps visible, assumed away. gives sentinel (Governance) something concrete monitor compliance against. · wu=Establishing updating security control framework business., "Which control covers X," "map NIST/ISO/SOC 2," "what's our control gap.", new system/process needs controls identified (feeds risk-register). · st:/ Protocol=CHOOSE STANDARD (config `control_standard` NIST CSF default; installs matching GRC pack) MAP (the pack's control catalog business's systems/data/people; control gets OWNER: agent, operator, another dept) POLICY SET (the human-readable policies implementing controls access, encryption, IR, acceptable-use; assets/isms-policy-index.md) STATUS (each control: implemented partial gap not-applicable-with-reason silent gaps) EVIDENCE (what proves control works feeds sentinel's compliance monitoring) CHANGE (material policy changes route anneal board, Fleet Charter Rail senior charters unchanged). · in=**Standard first, map.** operator picks control standard (§8.4); warden installs GRC pack maps catalog *this* business control applies, non-applicable ones marked reason, never silently dropped. **Every control owner.** control nobody owns control nobody does. Owners agents (e.g., keyring owns access controls, bastion owns config baselines), operator (privileged actions), another dept (sentinel owns compliance evidence). **Wrap pack, don't reinvent it.** GRC pack supplies authoritative control text (benchmarked, maintained); warden adds mapping, ownership, status, this-business specifics. Don't hand-write NIST controls pack already has. **No silent gaps.** control implemented, partial, gap, N/A-with-reason. Gaps risk-register (sibling) risks treat gap risk, tracked, ignored (the department's core rule). **Policy human-readable owned.** Policies implement controls plain language people follow; owner review date (dated, like ops's playbooks). **Charters senior; changes gated.** Engineering Security Charter Fleet Charter outrank ISMS; material policy changes route through board (Rail 3). warden writes policy maps controls; execute privileged changes (the security-inversion). · of=`## ISMS: [business] — standard: [NIST CSF / ISO 27001 / SOC 2 / CIS] \· Control map: [control \· owner \· status(impl/partial/gap/N-A+reason) \· evidence] \· Gaps → risk-register: [refs] \· Policy set: [policy \· owner \· review date] (assets/isms-policy-index.md) \· Change: [material → board (Rail 3) / routine logged]` · pr=**Standard-mapped, this-business specific** pack's catalog, warden's mapping., **Every control owned; silent gaps** gap tracked risk., **Wrap, don't reinvent** authoritative pack content warden's discipline., **Charters senior; changes board-gated** ISMS sits under operator-owned law., **warden writes policy, never holds keys** security-inversion. · f=pack installed standard unchosen map against sensible default subset (CIS Controls IG1 universal baseline), labeled provisional, surface pack adoption (scout/operator)., Small business, full standard overkill scope crown-jewel-relevant controls first (risk-based, checkbox-complete), stated. · b:with Other Skills=**risk-register** (sibling): gaps become risks there; two ISMS's two halves (controls risks)., **sentinel (Governance)**: monitors *compliance* against framework's evidence; warden owns framework, sentinel monitors adherence clean split., **board (Governance)**: material policy changes gate (Rail 3); risk acceptance too., Control owners across fleet: keyring (access), bastion (config/network), cortex (detection/IR), veil (data/privacy), quinn (agent-runtime rails), dana (data Rail 3).